  <div class="mx-auto max-w-6xl px-4 sm:px-6">
    <h2 id="about-title" class="text-2xl font-bold text-[var(--card-text)] sm:text-3xl mb-6">
      About this directory
    </h2>
    <div class="max-w-none text-base leading-[1.6] text-[var(--card-text-muted)] space-y-4">
      <p>
        <strong>What this site is:</strong> Directorio Morado is a free, public directory
        of support resources for survivors of sexual violence and people seeking reproductive
        and abortion support in Mexico and Latin America. Entries are stored in a curated
        database and shown on the site; anyone can suggest a resource via the site,
        and suggestions are reviewed by administrators before publication. It is not
        a government site and is not run by a single organization. No fee is charged
        for listings.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Who maintains it:</strong> The directory is maintained as a public
        resource for the community. Administrators curate and approve entries. The
        public can submit new resources through the “Sugerir un recurso” (suggest a
        resource) form; submissions go to a pending queue and appear in the directory
        only after approval.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>What type of resources it lists:</strong> The directory lists organizations,
        collectives, professionals, and government services. Resource types include:
        crisis hotlines (24/7), abortion accompaniment, psychological support, legal
        support, community support, sexual violence support, reproductive rights,
        sexual health, financial support, government services, nutrition support,
        medical and health, and associations and foundations. Each entry can indicate
        cost (free, low cost, variable, or consult directly), population served (e.g.
        women, girls, survivors of sexual violence, general public), and whether
        the service is online, in-person, or both. Coverage is Mexico and Latin America
        and the Caribbean (e.g. Mexico, Guatemala, Colombia, Argentina, Chile, Brazil,
        and other countries in the region).
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>How you use it:</strong> You can browse and filter the directory by
        type of support, search by name or location, and open individual entries for
        contact details (phone, WhatsApp, website, Instagram, hours). No registration
        or login is required to view the directory. Use is anonymous; the site does
        not collect personal data from visitors.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Who it is for:</strong> This directory is for survivors of sexual
        violence, women and people seeking abortion or reproductive rights support,
        and anyone in Mexico or Latin America looking for psychological, legal, crisis,
        or community support in these areas.
      </p>
      <p>
        <strong>Emergency disclaimer:</strong> Directorio Morado is an information
        directory, not emergency services. If you are in immediate danger, call 911.
        For 24-hour crisis support in Mexico, call 800 911 2000.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
